### Description

[Per some discussion on the Atom boards](https://discuss.atom.io/t/code-folding-close-bracket/9997) there's some concession that folded blocks of code can often be difficult to parse and work around.

Here are some examples of the current behavior and a suggested change to make the fold easier to parse.

``` js
// Example code
function () {
  console.log('Hello world.');
  console.log('How are you today?');
}

/*
 * How Atom currently handles folds within a given syntax
 */
// Folding the function - Atom (JavaScript syntax)
function () {...

/*
 * What I expect to happen to happen in a given syntax
 */
// Folding the function - Atom (Plain Text syntax)
function () {
}

// Folding the function - Sublime Text
function () {
}

// A one-line variation
function () {..}
```

And another example using HTML

``` html
<!-- Example code -->
<section>
  <p>Hello world.</p>
</section>

<!--
 How Atom currently handles folds within a given syntax
 -->
<!-- Folding the block - Atom (HTML syntax) -->
<section>...

<!--
 What I expect to happen to happen in a given syntax
 -->
<!-- Folding the block - Atom (Plain Text syntax) -->
<section>
</section>

<!-- Folding the block - Sublime Text -->
<section>
</section>

<!-- A one-line variation -->
<section>...</section>
```

The `Atom (Plain Text syntax)` and `Sublime Text` format is easier to parse because it's clear where the function/block starts and stops. It also makes wrapping a folded block with more code easier because you can see the beginning and end of the full statement.

The other problem with the current Atom folding method is indenting a folded function does not work properly.

**JavaScript Example**:
![Indenting folded JavaScript in Atom](https://zippy.gfycat.com/ExcellentMerryCoyote.gif)

**HTML Example**:
![Indenting folded HTML in Atom](https://zippy.gfycat.com/FarTenseAdeliepenguin.gif)

@lee-dohm suggested I provide some examples of other folds besides just the [1TBS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indent_style#Variant:_1TBS) style. I've noted some proposals:

**Stroustrup**:

``` c++
// Example
class Vector { 
  public:
      Vector(int s) :elem(new double[s]), sz(s) { }
      double& operator[](int i) { return elem[i]; }
      int size() { return sz; } 
  private:
      double elem[lowast];
      int sz;
};

// Expected
class Vector {
  public:...
  private:...
}
```

**Allman**:

``` js
// Example
while (x == y)
{
  something();
  somethingelse();
}

// Expected
while (x == y)
{
}
```
### Steps to Reproduce
1. Launch Atom
2. In the correct syntax (not just "Plain Text"), write a multiline, indented function/block
3. Collapse block
4. (To replicate indentation issue) Indent the folded, one-line block
### Versions

**Atom**: 1.5.4
